"You might as well answer the door, my child,the truth is furiously knocking.\n\n- Lucille Clifton, Good Woman: Poems and a Memoir 1969-1980\n|\nAs long as I fight, I am moved by hope; and if I fight with hope, then I can wait.\n\n- Paulo Freire, Pedagogy of the Oppressed\n|\nWriters are always anxious, always on the run--from the telephone, from responsibilities, from the distractions of the world.\n\n- Edna\n|\nBooks should not be loved selfishly. Neither books nor anything else, in fact.\n\n- Marie-Sabine Roger, Das Labyrinth der Wörter\n|\nI’ve been working hard to become the kind of man she needs, the kind of man she already believes me to be.\n\n- Colleen\n|\nLive with God, have faith in God – it is true happiness\n\n- Sunday\n|\nIt costs me never a stab nor squirm / To tread by chance upon a worm. / Aha, my little dear, / I say, Your clan will pay me back one day.\n\n- Dorothy\n|\nIf you're always following the crowd, you will never truly know who you are. Walk your own path.\n\n- Julian\n|\nI give you this to take with you:Nothing remains as it was. If you know this, you canbegin again, with pure joy in the uprooting.\n\n- Judith Minty, Letters to My Daughters\n|\nAlways be truthful and you will have fewer visits from regret, guilt or fear.\n\n- Suzy Kassem, Rise Up and Salute the Sun: The Writings of Suzy Kassem\n|\nIf lawmakers in nations today refused to be bribed and be corrupted by some larger-than-life leaders, the people will be less insulted and molested by ungodliness and injustice.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nWhen she smiles, the lines in her face become epic narratives that trace the stories of generations that no book can replace.\n\n- Curtis\n|\nBe the girl you want your daughter to be. Be the girl you want your son to date. Be classy, be smart, be real, but most importantly be nice.\n\n- Germany\n|\nA writer is one who communicates ideas and emotions people want to communicate but aren't quite sure how, or even if, they should communicate them.\n\n- Criss Jami, Killosophy\n|\nWhere there’s life, there’s the hope of change.\n\n- Timothy Zahn, Choices of One\n|\nA doctorate study is the passion for extensive research, reading, thinking and writing.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nI knew I could do it all this time,” said Harry, “Because I'd already done it... does that make sense?\n\n- J.K. Rowling, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban\n|\nYesterday we obeyed kings and bent our necks before emperors. But today we kneel only to truth, follow only beauty, and obey only love.\n\n- Kahlil Gibran, The Vision: Reflections on the Way of the Soul\n|\nFaith doesn't move mountains, but people with faith - and shovels - will move mountains in order to defend their faith.\n\n- Aron\n|\nWe must not allow our pride to be the motivation behind our apologetics; rather, philoverity, the love of truth must be the full and complete motivation. For pride corrupts truth.\n\n- Criss\n|\nLike a caterpillar, when you feel that your time is over, you may reach infinite light with infinite joy.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nKnowledge was scattered treasure, education organized it into art, commerce and science.\n\n- Amit\n|\nThey're so cold, these scholars!May lightning strike their foodso that their mouths learn howto eat fire!\n\n- Friedrich\n|\nAsking questions is an essential daily habit, because your experiences are often in proportion to the questions you ask.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nYou are magnificent beyond measure, perfect in your imperfections, and wonderfully made.\n\n- Abiola Abrams, The Sacred Bombshell Handbook of Self-Love\n|\nWhen life gives you lemons, squirt someone in the eye.\n\n- Cathy\n|\nCharitably... I think... sometimes, perhaps, one must change or die. And, in the end, there were, perhaps, limits to how much he could let himself change.\n\n- Neil Gaiman, The Wake\n|\nWhen you take risks you learn that there will be times when you succeed and there will be times when you fail, and both are equally important.\n\n- Ellen DeGeneres, Seriously... I'm Kidding\n|\nOne thing I've learned about vampires--they keep pulling new rabbits out of their cloaks. Big, fanged, carnivorous bunnies that'll eat your eyeballs if you're not paying attention.\n\n- Laurell K. Hamilton, Bloody Bones\n|\nIf you know the art of finding some things in a quite empty street, then you know the art of happiness!\n\n- Mehmet\n|\nOf all the things I wish for her, above all, I want her to know and love the sea.\n\n- Laurie Nadel, Dancing with the Wind: A True Story of Zen in the Art of Windsurfing\n|\nOh, Life, I am yours. Whatever it is you want of me, I am ready to give.\n\n- William Steig, Dominic\n|\nWriting is supposed to be difficult, agonizing, a dreadful exercise, a terrible occupation.\n\n- Ray Bradbury, Zen in the Art of Writing\n|\nYou can have anything you need in life, the only price you have to pay is for you to exchange your life for greatness and greatness will deliver that thing you need to you.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, How To Become Great Through Time Conversion: Are you wasting time, spending time or investing time?\n|\nPeople say that life is the thing, but I prefer reading.\n\n- Logan\n|\nLike most modern people, I don't believe in prophecy or magic and then spend half my time practicing it.\n\n- John Steinbeck, The Winter of Our Discontent\n|\nDon't let what you fear stop you from pursuing it. For the most part, what you fear doesn't even know that you are afraid of it.\n\n- Dr.\n|\nI am troubled, immeasurablyby your eyes. I am struck by the featherof your soft reply.The sound of glassspeaks quick, disdainand concealswhat your eyes fightto explain.\n\n- Jim Morrison, Wilderness: The Lost Writings, Vol. 1\n|\nNo one conquers fear easily, Robert. It takes a brave heart to win great battles.\n\n- Peter Bunzl, Cogheart\n|\nLet's think the unthinkable, let's do the undoable. Let us prepare to grapple with the ineffable itself, and see if we may not eff it after all.\n\n- Douglas Adams, Dirk Gently's Holistic Detective Agency\n|\nTo find out what one is fitted to do, and to secure an opportunity to do it, is the key to happiness.\n\n- John\n|\nSometimes, the way around prejudice is education.\n\n- Liza Mundy, Michelle: A Biography\n|\nMan wants three things; life, knowledge, and love.\n\n- Fulton J. Sheen, Life Is Worth Living\n|\nMind knows the questions, soul knows the answers.\n\n- Amit\n|\nIf you didn’t fall down, you would never have learned how to pick yourself up.\n\n- Laurie Nadel, Dancing with the Wind: A True Story of Zen in the Art of Windsurfing\n|\nYou lie to her, you lie to me, you lie to yourself. Blind girl blind you.\n\n- Daniel Wallace, The Kings and Queens of Roam\n|\nHave you lost your hope? Have you remained inside the fog? Don’t worry; even if you can’t find it, a new hope will come and find you!\n\n- Mehmet\n|\nDo as I say, not as I do.\n\n- Swami Pranayomama, How To Not Give A F-ck In Ten Easy Steps: The Modern Lay Person's Guide To Enlightenment\n|\nIf the past was what we were meant to see…then behind, not in front, our eyes would be.\n\n- RVM\n|\nBut, luckily, he kept his wits and his purple crayon.\n\n- Crockett Johnson, Harold and the Purple Crayon\n|\nIf you want to change your future, you have to change your now, and to change your now you must change your mindset.\n\n- Anthony\n|\nA smiling lie is a whirlwind, easy to enter, but hard to escape.\n\n- Dejan Stojanovic, The Sun Watches the Sun\n|\nIf you don't keep track of great ideas, you'll stop noticing you have them.\n\n- Bogdan\n|\nThe less you know, the more you will be knownThe less you want, the more you will haveThe less you are, the more you will be\n\n- Vivian Amis, I Am: The Key to Manifesting\n|\nthose of us who read because we love it more than anything, who feel about bookstores the way some people feel about jewelers...\n\n- Anna Quindlen, How Reading Changed My Life\n|\nA happiness trick:do more things that make you happy, and you'll be happy more often.\n\n- Scott\n|\nIf you behave in a manner that poisons your relationship, don’t be surprised when it dies.\n\n- Steve\n|\nThe key to flow is to pursue an activity for its own sake, not for the rewards it brings.\n\n- Susan Cain, Quiet: The Power of Introverts in a World That Can't Stop Talking\n|\nLike everything else, Fletcher. Practice.\n\n- Richard Bach, Jonathan Livingston Seagull\n|\nNo one could ever truly be free as long as they loved, and life wasn't worth living without love. So freedom? Overrated.\n\n- Gena Showalter, Unraveled\n|\nWe travel to new places, with every book, we read.\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nIf you were called to gallop like the horse, never end up hopping like the frog. Rise up for greatness.\n\n- Israelmore Ayivor, Become a Better You\n|\nLife said to me, Be happy. Don't let me down.\n\n- Marty\n|\nTo make him important in one’s life requires an overactive imagination. Unfortunately, mine never knows when to quit.\n\n- Carrie Fisher, The Princess Diarist\n|\nA book is good company. It is full of conversation without loquacity. It comes to your longing with full instruction, but pursues you never.\n\n- Henry\n|\nWhen we face every challenge with optimism and learn to fail with our heads up, a great attitude is always success, no matter the outcome.\n\n- Ron Baratono, The Writings of Ron Baratono\n|\nI am not too worried about the many changes in today's society, but I am rather overly concerned about societies refusal to change from it destructive path!\n\n- Lawrence Sankar, Beloved Hear My Heart\n|\nNjoy Life to the extend, at which you make the moment and you live it\n\n- Rhouveyzz\n|\nLiving someone else's vision, is proclaiming death to your imparted destiny, and proclaiming life to the destiny of the visionaries pursuing their visions.\n\n- Wayne\n|\nWe had some good times at school. I didn't know how good those times was till I left, but I guess that's the way of it\n\n- Ron Rash, Serena\n|\nI have no name,' she purred. 'I'm whoever the keepers of my fate tell me to be.\n\n- Sarah J. Maas, The Assassin and the Underworld\n|\nDon’t try to change the world. To find yourself in a new world, change your thoughts.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nThe secret of happiness is to see all the marvels of the world, and never to forget the drops of oil on the spoon.\n\n- Paulo Coelho, The Alchemist\n|\nMy meanness has an ego too, often bigger than my own.\n\n- Angelos Michalopoulos, The man who has only one truth in him\n|\nThe day we find the perfect church, it becomes imperfect the moment we join it.\n\n- Charles\n|\nAs long as one sees faults with the world, he prevails in the knowledge of the senses. The inner purification has not yet occurred in him.\n\n- Dada\n|\nOpen the fridge and putMy heart on a plate.I'm just as you leftme, and I taste even betterleftover.\n\n- Cecily von Ziegesar, Don't You Forget About Me\n|\nI could not love thee, Dear, so much, Loved I not Honour more.\n\n- Richard Lovelace, The Lucasta Poems\n|\nSpirituality is for people. It’s not just for those who you might have read about in books, it’s for people.\n\n- Belsebuub\n|\nMixing old wine with new wine is stupidity, but mixing old wisdom with new wisdom is maturity.\n\n- Amit Kalantri, Wealth of Words\n|\nPeople ask me all the time, 'Where do your ideas come from?' So, to clear up this question...I keep my ideas inside the mind of a tiny man who is tied up in my closet!\n\n- C.K.\n|\nHappiness does not depend on outward circumstances, but on the state of the heart.\n\n- J.C. Ryle, A Call to Prayer\n|\nMom asked for a cupcake miracle? Well, here comes the freaking holy angel of icing, at your service. --\n\n- Sarah Ockler, Bittersweet\n|\nI loved you like a man loves a woman he never touches, only writes to, keeps little photographs of.\n\n- Charles Bukowski, Love Is a Dog from Hell\n|\nBut to her, libraries were like hotels: secret villages inhabited by passing strangers from a thousand different worlds brought together just for a few hours.\n\n- Simon\n|\nThere's a lesson here, and that is I have to find happiness inside myself before I try to partner again.\n\n- Ellen Hopkins, Traffick\n|\nChildren know perfectly well that unicorns aren’t real, but they also know that books about unicorns, if they are good books, are true books.\n\n- Ursula\n|\nIn the end, it wasn't death that surprised her but the stubbornness of life.\n\n- Jeffrey Eugenides, The Virgin Suicides\n|\nThe soul should always stand ajar, ready to welcome the ecstatic experience.\n\n- Emily\n|\nYou are, after all, what you think. Your emotions are the slaves to your thoughts, and you are the slave to your emotions.\n\n- Elizabeth Gilbert, Eat, Pray, Love\n|\nI have a pretty large experience of boys, and you're a bad set of fellows. Now mind!\n\n- Charles Dickens, Great Expectations\n|\nThat's your truck parked up by the factory isn't it?' Magnus pointed. 'It's awfully butch for a bookseller.\n\n- Cassandra Clare, City of Ashes\n|\nBecause fear called her by her name. (Her own name, not fear’s name. Fear doesn’t have a name; it’s just the steady beat underneath a smile.)\n\n- Luisa Valenzuela, Dark Desires and the Others\n|\nIf someone tries to use you as a tool, you shouldn't mind it, because it is their choice and folly, not yours.\n\n- Jude Morgan, Indiscretion\n|\nSometimes I succeed, sometimes I fail, but everyday is a clean state and a fresh opportunity.\n\n- Gretchen\n|\nOnce you choose hope, anything's possible.\n\n- Christopher\n|\nThe hardest thing of all is to find a black cat in a dark room, especially if there is no cat.\n\n- Confucius\n|\nIt's never the differences between people that surprise us. It's the things that, against all odds, we have in common.\n\n- Jodi Picoult, House Rules\n|\nDifficulties strengthen the mind, as labor does the body.\n\n- Seneca\n|\nAllow not, the shallow intentions or vile aspirations of others to taint your heart; Love always. - With an abundance of positivity you will counter the negative, always.\n\n- Tiffany"